Scope of the Observatory Standard

The SSUM-AIM Observatory defines a deterministic certification framework for verifying structural properties of computation through manifest-certified replay identity.

Each certification kernel produces deterministic certificate artifacts whose integrity is governed by manifest verification and replay identity.

Core deterministic certification discipline:

Replay identity invariant:

B_A = B_B

Where:

• B_A = certification artifact set from execution A
• B_B = certification artifact set from execution B

Replay identity confirms deterministic structural integrity.

The Observatory establishes:

• deterministic certification kernels
• manifest-certified artifact integrity
• replay-verifiable execution discipline
• tamper-evident certification artifacts
• reproducible structural certification

What the Observatory Does NOT Do

The SSUM-AIM Observatory does not:

• modify classical computation
• alter algorithm outputs
• introduce probabilistic inference
• perform machine learning
• inject predictive models
• simulate future behavior
• introduce randomness
• alter execution semantics

It provides deterministic certification only.

It certifies structural truth of execution.

It does not control execution.

Conformance

An implementation conforms to the SSUM-AIM Observatory Standard if it:

• executes deterministically
• produces manifest-certified artifacts
• preserves artifact integrity under hashing
• produces byte-identical certification artifacts under replay

Conformance authority condition:

B_A = B_B

Any implementation introducing:

• randomness
• probabilistic inference
• nondeterministic output ordering
• hidden state mutation
• tolerance-based comparison
• adaptive runtime mutation

does not conform to the SSUM-AIM Observatory deterministic certification standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.

